// =============================================================================
// Samavāya BI — Report Service
// =============================================================================
// The report service is the "designer + runner" layer of the BI platform.
// A Report is a saved, user-configurable query binding — it references a
// Dataset, picks a subset of fields, applies filters / groupings / sorts,
// and attaches a chart type. Reports execute through the query service
// internally but expose their own lifecycle: runs, exports, schedules,
// subscriptions, alerts, and folder organisation.
//
// Power BI equivalent: paginated reports + Power BI datasets-as-sources.
// Looker equivalent:   Looks (saved visualisations on an Explore).
//
// Consolidation notes
// -------------------
// This service absorbs three legacy modules:
//   * business/insights/insighthub      — designer (fields/filters/groups/sorts/charts)
//   * business/insights/insightviewer   — execution, export, schedule, subscription, alert, cache
//   * business/insights/savedsearch     — folders, favorites, shares, schedules (folder-centric subset)
//
// savedsearch's "scheduled saved search" and insightviewer's "report
// schedule" are the same concept with different names. Merging them
// eliminates the duplication — one Schedule entity, one CreateSchedule RPC.
// Folders from savedsearch become first-class here because users want to
// organise their reports.
//
// Design principles
// -----------------
//   * A Report is immutable in identity (id + key); its body is mutable.
//     Structural changes (fields/filters/groups/sorts) are audited.
//   * Reports consume datasets but do NOT re-model them. All semantic
//     weight lives in core/bi/dataset.
//   * Execution delegates to core/bi/query by translating Report state
//     into a VisualQuery. Callers that need low-level control should call
//     QueryService directly; Report is the high-level, saveable surface.
//   * Exports are async. ExportReport returns an ExportJob; the client
//     polls GetExportStatus / DownloadExport.
//   * Schedules run in the background and create ReportRun rows; the
//     notification side-effect (email/in-app) is handled by subscribers.
//   * Alerts evaluate a predicate against each run's result and fire when
//     the condition transitions from false → true. They do not poll the
//     query directly — they consume schedule runs.
//
// Related docs
// ------------
//   * docs/BI_CONSOLIDATION_ROADMAP.md — Sprint 5 implementation
//   * docs/adr/0001-bi-platform-consolidation.md
// =============================================================================

